  <h1>Class Action Guides</h1>
  <p>Plain-language guides written and reviewed by editorial staff with experience in class action litigation support and settlement administration. Each guide explains the legal and practical context behind the calculator results.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/how-class-action-settlements-work/">How Class Action Settlements Work</a></h2>
  <p>The complete process from preliminary approval through final distribution: the court&rsquo;s role in approving the settlement, the claims notice and filing period, the fairness hearing, the appeals risk from professional objectors, and how funds actually reach class members. Covers attorney fee analysis, cy pres distributions, and the timeline from agreement to check.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/types-of-class-action-cases/">Types of Class Action Cases</a></h2>
  <p>Consumer fraud, data breach (including BIPA statutory damages), securities fraud under PSLRA, employment and wage-and-hour, and product liability / MDL — with the specific settlement dynamics, claims rates, and individual recovery ranges that characterize each type. Explains why individual share sizes vary so dramatically across case types.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/filing-a-class-action-claim/">Filing a Class Action Claim</a></h2>
  <p>How to find settlements you qualify for, complete claim forms correctly, understand what documentation is required, watch claims deadlines, evaluate whether to opt out, and track your payment through the distribution process. Practical guidance for maximizing recovery from class action settlements you are entitled to.</p>

  <h2><a href="/guides/class-action-misconceptions/">Common Class Action Misconceptions</a></h2>
  <p>Five widely held misunderstandings about class action lawsuits: the gap between headline settlement numbers and individual payouts, the claims filing requirement, the attorney fee structure, opt-out rights, and what it means when the settlement includes no admission of wrongdoing. Each misconception explained with the actual legal standard and practical implications.</p>

